  <!-- How Roller Conveyors Work -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Technical Deep-Dive</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How Roller Conveyors <span class="text-accent">Work</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Every roller conveyor shares the same basic structure: cylindrical rollers rotate on bearings seated in side frames. Products ride on top of the rollers. The rollers either spin freely (gravity) or are driven by an external force (powered). Frame construction uses formed steel channel or structural angle in gauges from 7 to 12, depending on load capacity.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Roller Construction</h3>
        <p>Standard conveyor rollers consist of a steel or aluminum tube, two precision bearings (typically ABEC-1 or ABEC-3), and a hex or spring-loaded axle. Roller diameter ranges from 1.375 inches (light duty) to 3.5 inches (heavy duty). Wall thickness ranges from 16-gauge (0.065") for light cases to 7-gauge (0.180") for heavy pallets. Manufacturers like Interroll, Rulmeca, and Dematic-Hytrol offer rollers in carbon steel, stainless steel, PVC, and aluminum.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Exact ABEC ratings offered by Interroll vs Rulmeca for standard conveyor rollers -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Roller Spacing (Pitch)</h3>
        <p>Roller pitch determines how many rollers contact the product at any time. The universal rule requires at least 3 rollers under the product at all times. Common pitch values include 1.5", 2", 3", 4.5", and 6" center-to-center. Closer pitch provides smoother transport for small or lightweight items. Wider pitch reduces cost and suits large, heavy products. Hytrol publishes a detailed roller pitch selection table in their engineering manual that cross-references product length to recommended pitch.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Bearing Types</h3>
        <p>Conveyor roller bearings come in three grades. Precision ball bearings (lowest rolling resistance) suit <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/gravity/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">gravity roller conveyors</a> where minimal force must move the product. Standard ball bearings work for <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/powered/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">powered roller conveyors</a> where the drive system overcomes bearing friction. Sealed and lubricated-for-life bearings dominate <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food and beverage</a> applications where contamination risk prohibits re-lubrication.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Frame Types</h3>
        <p>Roller conveyor frames use three common profiles. Channel frame (C-channel) offers the highest strength-to-weight ratio for heavy-duty applications. Angle frame (L-shaped) provides a <a href="/conveyor-types/low-profile-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">low-profile</a>, economical option for light-duty gravity sections. Structural tube frame suits custom fabrications and <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sanitary stainless steel designs</a>. Frame widths range from 12" to 60" between rails. Support heights range from 24" to 42" for standard floor-mounted installations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

