  <!-- Selection Criteria -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Criteria</div>
      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How to Select a <span class="text-accent">Roller Conveyor</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Selecting the right roller conveyor requires matching six parameters to available equipment.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">1. Product bottom surface.</strong> Roller conveyors require a flat, rigid bottom surface. Soft bags, pouches, and irregular shapes fall between rollers and require belt conveyors instead. The product bottom must span at least 3 rollers at the chosen pitch.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">2. Product weight.</strong> Individual product weight determines roller diameter, wall thickness, bearing type, and frame gauge. Light cases (under 50 lbs) use 1.9" diameter rollers in light-gauge frames. Heavy pallets (over 500 lbs) require 3.5" rollers in structural frames with heavy-duty bearings.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">3. Speed and throughput.</strong> Calculate required speed from your throughput formula. <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/gravity/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Gravity systems</a> provide variable, uncontrolled speed. Powered systems provide consistent, adjustable speed. Match the conveyor speed to your upstream and downstream equipment rates.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">4. Accumulation requirement.</strong> If products must queue without backpressure, select <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR</a> or pneumatic <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation conveyors</a>. Continuous transport without accumulation allows simpler <a href="/conveyor-types/live-roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">live roller</a> or gravity configurations.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">5. Environment.</strong> Wet or <a href="/conveyor-types/washdown-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">washdown environments</a> require stainless steel rollers, sealed bearings, and corrosion-resistant frames. Standard warehouse environments use galvanized or painted carbon steel. High-temperature environments require special bearing lubricants and heat-resistant materials.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">6. Budget.</strong> <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/gravity/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Gravity roller</a> costs the least per foot. <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR</a> costs more upfront but saves on energy and maintenance over the conveyor's 15-20 year life. <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR</a> costs more due to heavier construction but handles loads that lighter conveyors cannot. See the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for factor-by-factor cost breakdowns.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

